  "texts": [
    "Within professional personas, model heterogeneity ranges from 2.8% to 73.6%.",
    "This 26-fold variation demonstrates that some models maintain robust disclosure while others fail almost entirely.within the 10-30B parameter range alone, models vary by 56.9 percentage points.",
    "This within-sizeclass heterogeneity appears across all parameter ranges: 33pp for very small models under 10B, 57pp for small models from 10-30B, 61pp for medium models from 30-200B, and 53pp for large models above 200B; see Figures 456in Appendix D. For instance, GPT-OSS-20B achieves 70.5% overall disclosure while Mistral-Small-3.2-24B-Inst achieves 13.6% overall disclosure, representing a 57 percentage point difference in overall performance among models with similar architectural scale from 14B-27B that differ by less than 2× in size.",
    "Self-Transparency is Model-Specific, Not Scale-DependentTo formally test whether parameter count or model identity better fits the disclosure data, we employed three complementary statistical approaches:• Test 1 (Incremental Adjusted R2): Beyond baseline controls for persona and prompt effects, adding parameter count yielded Δ𝑅 2 adj = 0.018, while adding model identity yielded Δ𝑅 2 adj = 0.359; see Table 8.",
    "The identity model yields substantially larger gains even after penalizing for its additional complexity.• Test 2 (Wald Tests): Both parameter count and model identity achieve statistical significance in their respective models; all chi-square tests yield p < 0.001 for main effects and persona interactions."
